<br>
1. It's good for women. Birth control is possible the single most important factor in women's liberation. This is not to say that suffrage and economic power are not, but they would not be fully realized by women without reproductive freedom. The leading cause of death for women until the early 20th century was childbirth, the average woman not only started having children earlier than we do today--she stopped later and was therefore tied to her home and pregnant most of her reproductive life. The implications of this go beyond how healthy it is to have 12 or 14 kids one after another for the mother and/or children (we are much better off today and can ensure better health and more space between children and a mother conceiving only when her body is ready) to the issue of how in the heck a woman can get out there and go to school and work and get daycare and run for congress etc. without control of her own body. The pill in particular had a huuuuuge impact on the women's movement and our ability to exercise these freedoms and newly found powers.<br>
<br>
2. It's good for kids. Like I said in the paragraph above, not being able to use birth control for whatever reason can lead to unhealthy women conceiving which is never good for the kid. If a women doesn't want a child or is in no position to carry one (alcoholic, prostitute, HIV positive) it is particularly important she have the ability to prevent a pregnancy. Mistakes happen and most babies are not planned out that meticulously, but with more and more women waiting until they are educated, financially stable and under a doctor's care to carry a child the ultimate winner is that baby.<br>
<br>
3. It's good for society. When women have more social/economic/political/reproductive freedom, regardless of religion or party, there is more open discussion, benefit to society from the full use of her skills and having a happy, fulfilled, productive woman. This doesn't have to mean a woman not having children at all, rather having how many she wants and can handle when she is ready with the support she needs---they are less likely to go on welfare, be born with handicaps the tax payers foot the bill for or have developmental problems themselves. I could go on and on here but...<br>
<br>
4. It's good for the environment. The extent to which we are depleting our resources, especially in the industrialized countries is just plain nuts and each of our children destroy 10 times more than kids in 3rd world countries. Either way, overpopulation has startling consequences and we best get a handle on this real soon. I remember someone here saying the earth kills of humans every once in a while, but not since the dinosaurs died out has extinction occured on a large enough scale to help and we weren't around yet. There are 6 355 543.4 billion people in the world and number is expected to increase by 50% in the next 50 years!! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> The rate at which we consume and degrade natural resources jeopardizes the health of the planet and threatens the availability of clean water for generations to come. Almost one-half of the global population is under the age of 25 (too, too many babies=not adequate access or ability to use birth control), the choices families make today will have a tremendous impact on the future.<br>
<br>
